## Decisions based on interim A/B-test results

Suppose your team has finished a new feature and wants to test it with an A/B
test. Before launch, you choose the primary KPI, the smallest effect worth
detecting, and a 5% false-positive rate. A power calculation turns these
choices into a runtime: twenty days. The team fixes that runtime and launches.

Fixing the runtime settles when the decision will be made. It does not change
what everyone sees in the meantime. Whether the experimentation platform is
built in-house or supplied by GrowthBook, Eppo, Statsig, or Optimizely, the
dashboard recomputes the treatment estimate and p-value each morning, and
anyone on the team can look.

On day one, the estimated effect is positive and the p-value is 0.15. On day
two, the p-value is 0.08. On day three, it falls below 0.05 and stays there
through day eight. By day three, the team is discussing whether to ship. The
test already looks significant, so why wait another seventeen days?

Because the p-value on the dashboard was not calibrated for that decision. Its
5% false-positive rate is a property of one prespecified analysis: fit the
model once, on day twenty, and reject if $p \leq 0.05$. Shipping on day three
replaces this plan with a different procedure, one that checks the p-value
every day and acts the first time it dips below 0.05. The daily procedure
gives sampling noise up to twenty chances to produce a significant-looking
result instead of one.

How much do the extra chances matter? If the twenty daily analyses were
independent, at least one of them would fall below 0.05 in a null experiment
with probability $1 - (1 - 0.05)^{20} \approx 0.64$. They are not independent,
since each day's analysis reuses all the data from the days before, so 64%
overstates the problem. The actual false-positive rate of daily stopping lies
somewhere between 5% and 64%, and Scenario 1 below measures it by simulation.
The qualitative point does not need a simulation, though: the 5% guarantee
covers the prespecified day-twenty analysis and nothing else.

::: {.callout}
The problem is not opening the dashboard every day. It arises when the interim
results can trigger a decision to stop, ship, roll back, or extend the
experiment.
:::

**Anytime-valid inference** is built for exactly this situation: repeated
looks at accumulating data, any of which may trigger a decision.

## What SAVI changes

Safe anytime-valid inference (SAVI) replaces the ordinary p-value and
confidence interval with sequential counterparts whose guarantees survive
this kind of monitoring. In the large randomized experiments considered here,
a 5% SAVI test is calibrated so that, under the method's assumptions, the
probability that a null experiment *ever* shows a sequential p-value at or
below 0.05 is asymptotically at most 5%. "Ever" is the operative word. The
guarantee holds across all days at once, so the review schedule does not have
to be chosen before launch, and a prespecified rule such as "ship the first
time the SAVI p-value falls below 0.05" keeps the 5% error rate. The
sequential p-value has an interval companion, the **confidence sequence**: a
sequence of intervals that contains the true effect at every review
simultaneously, with asymptotic probability of at least 95%.

The stronger guarantee costs width. At the same sample size, a confidence
sequence is wider than an ordinary confidence interval, and the sequential
p-value is larger than the ordinary one, because both have to remain valid at
every possible stopping point rather than at one prespecified date. How much
this hurts depends on the true effect. A lift well above the one used in the
power calculation crosses the 0.05 threshold early, often well before day
twenty; a lift near or below the planning value typically takes longer to
detect than under the fixed-horizon test. Scenario 2 quantifies both cases.

The rest of this guide plays these properties out in five scenarios, each
built around a decision a product team routinely faces. Scenario 1 measures
how many false positives daily stopping produces in experiments where the
treatment does nothing, with and without SAVI. Scenario 2 asks when a feature
that genuinely works can ship early. The last three scenarios rely on
confidence sequences rather than p-values: certifying a backend migration as
harmless (Scenario 3), reporting a long-term holdout at weekly reviews
(Scenario 4), and rolling back a harmful canary release (Scenario 5). After
the scenarios, we show how regression adjustment narrows the confidence
sequence, walk through the `PyFixest` API, and collect the assumptions behind
the guarantee.

All simulations use `PyFixest`'s implementation of the linear-model method of
[Lindon et al. (2026)](https://doi.org/10.1080/01621459.2026.2692052), which
combines anytime-valid inference with regression adjustment for variance
reduction.^[Its closed-form formulas also make the method fast to compute.]

