An ordinary analysis performed only on day twenty rejects
5\.2% of the time, close to the intended 5%.
Checking the ordinary p-value daily and stopping at the first rejection raises
the rate to 25%. This is below the 64%
back-of-the-envelope number from the introduction because the twenty analyses
reuse the same accumulating data and are far from independent. It is
nevertheless several times the specified 5%. SAVI rejects
1\.0% of the same null experiments.

The SAVI false-positive rate need not equal 5%. Under the method's assumptions,
the probability of making a false rejection at any time is asymptotically at
most 5%. The probability of rejecting by day twenty is therefore also at most
5% and can be lower.

False positives are not the only damage that daily stopping causes; the
reported effect sizes suffer as well. Estimates are noisiest in the first
days, and a rule that stops at the first p-value below 0.05 stops exactly when
that noise happens to look like a large effect. So beyond asking how often
each rule rejects a null experiment, we should ask what estimate it reports
when it does. For each experiment that rejects, the second plot records the
estimate on its first rejection day; experiments that never reject are
omitted.

