::: {.figure-caption}
Estimated effects at the first rejection, among experiments that reject within twenty days. Non-rejecting experiments are omitted.
:::

The daily ordinary-p-value stopping rule rejects in
25% of these zero-effect experiments.
Among the experiments that reject, the estimated effect at the stopping time
averages 3\.9 pp in absolute value even though the
true effect is zero. These large magnitudes arise from selection at the
stopping time.

SAVI, whose threshold demands stronger evidence because it budgets for
repeated checks, rejects only
1\.0% of these null experiments. When it does
stop, however, the point estimate is still selected by the stopping rule and
overstates the effect in the same way. A stopping decision should therefore be
reported together with a confidence sequence rather than a bare point
estimate. Scenario 2 returns to this point.

## Scenario 2: effect size and stopping time

Scenario 1 dealt with features that do nothing. This scenario turns to the
case early stopping is meant for: a feature that works better than planned.
The A/B test was powered at about 80% to detect a lift from 10% to 12% after
twenty days; in this simulation, conversion rises to 14% instead, twice the
planned effect. The fixed-sample decision remains scheduled for day twenty, so
the question is how much earlier a prespecified SAVI rule supports a valid
ship decision.

We first follow one such experiment, chosen so that its SAVI stopping day is
the median among the 100 simulated experiments that reject by day twenty.

The top panel tracks the estimated lift together with an ordinary 95%
confidence interval and a 95% confidence sequence; the ordinary interval has
pointwise coverage at a prespecified analysis time, the confidence sequence
time-uniform asymptotic coverage. The bottom panel shows the ordinary and SAVI
p-values on a $-\log_{10}(p)$ scale, which keeps both threshold crossings
readable after the p-values become very small; the horizontal line corresponds
to $p=0.05$.

