::: {.figure-caption}
One simulated experiment with a true lift of 4 pp. The orange and blue vertical lines mark the first ordinary and SAVI p-values at or below 0.05. The evidence axis is capped at 4 so that the $p = 0.05$ line remains visible.
:::

The ordinary p-value falls below 0.05 on day 3, when the
estimated lift is 4\.5%. Acting on it would repeat the mistake
from the introduction: the ordinary procedure was calibrated for the
prespecified day-twenty decision, and stopping at its first value below 0.05
hands sampling variation up to twenty opportunities to cross the threshold.

The SAVI p-value falls below 0.05 on day 7, after
2\,800 users. Because the SAVI rule was prespecified and its
guarantee covers every day at once, the team can ship with
13 days left in the planned runtime. The result to report
alongside that decision is the confidence sequence, \[0\.3%\, 8\.0%\]. As in
Scenario 1, a rule that stops when evidence is strong selects estimates that
look favorable, so the point estimate on the stopping day tends to overstate
the true lift; the confidence sequence retains its coverage at the stopping
time.

One experiment shows a single stopping day. To see how the stopping time
depends on the true effect, a second simulation follows lifts of 1, 2, and 4
percentage points for forty days:

::: {#7a8d64b8 .cell execution_count=10}
``` {.python .cell-code code-fold="true" code-summary="Show the simulation code"}
MDE_MONITORING_DAYS = 40

handcuffs = _simulate_paths(
    p_control=0.10,
    p_treatment=0.10 + PLANNED_MDE,
    seed=10_000,
    n_days=MDE_MONITORING_DAYS,
)
smaller_effect_paths = _simulate_paths(
    p_control=0.10,
    p_treatment=0.11,
    seed=11_000,
    n_days=MDE_MONITORING_DAYS,
)
larger_effect_paths = _simulate_paths(
    p_control=0.10,
    p_treatment=0.14,
    seed=12_000,
    n_days=MDE_MONITORING_DAYS,
)

savi_detected = np.maximum.accumulate(
    (handcuffs["savi_p"] <= ALPHA) & (handcuffs["estimate"] > 0),
    axis=1,
)
savi_detection = savi_detected.mean(axis=0)
smaller_savi_detection = np.maximum.accumulate(
    (smaller_effect_paths["savi_p"] <= ALPHA)
    & (smaller_effect_paths["estimate"] > 0),
    axis=1,
).mean(axis=0)
larger_savi_detection = np.maximum.accumulate(
    (larger_effect_paths["savi_p"] <= ALPHA)
    & (larger_effect_paths["estimate"] > 0),
    axis=1,
).mean(axis=0)
oneshot_power = (
    (handcuffs["regular_p"][:, N_DAYS - 1] <= ALPHA)
    & (handcuffs["estimate"][:, N_DAYS - 1] > 0)
).mean()
```
