::: {.figure-caption}
Share of SAVI experiments with a valid positive decision by each day, for true lifts of 1, 2, and 4 pp. The fixed-test curve reports power for a true 2 pp lift at its prespecified decision time, day twenty.
:::

At day twenty, the fixed-horizon test detects the effect in
80% of experiments when the true lift is the
planned 2 pp. By then, SAVI has stopped in
99% of experiments with a
4 pp lift, 49% with a 2 pp lift,
and 8% with a 1 pp lift.
Because SAVI remains valid after the planned endpoint, the experiment can
continue. By day forty, those shares are
100%,
86%, and
23%, respectively.

Many 4 pp effects support a ship decision before day twenty. Effects at the
2 pp planning value frequently need longer, and 1 pp effects longer still. At
the planning value, SAVI detects fewer effects by day twenty than the
fixed-horizon test: its threshold is stricter precisely because it stays valid
under continued monitoring, and here that strictness shows up as waiting
time.

## Scenario 3: certify a backend migration

The first two scenarios asked whether an effect exists. A backend migration
turns the question around: the team wants evidence that there is no effect
worth worrying about. A checkout service is moving to a new backend, and the
team will approve the move only after the data rule out a conversion change of
1 pp or more in either direction. Approval therefore requires an interval that
lies entirely inside -1 to +1 pp.

The natural procedure is to review the result each day and certify the
migration as soon as the interval fits into that acceptance range. The
certification day is then chosen by the results, and just as with the daily
p-value checks of Scenario 1, an ordinary fixed-time confidence interval does
not support such a rule; a confidence sequence does. The A/A-style test sends
2,000 users per arm per day to the old and new backends. The displayed path
has the median confidence-sequence certification day among 100 simulations
that certify within thirty days.

::: {#22c25e6e .cell execution_count=12}
